#### Introduction to While Loops

##### Vocabulary

- **While Loop**: a looping structure that evaluates a conditional and repeats the body of the loop until the conditional is not longer true. For example, you might dig through your writing utensils until you find a blue pen. You don’t know how many pens you’ll need to look at before you find a blue one, so you will need to check pen color however many times it takes to find a blue pen. Let’s consider another example. 

<img src="https://images.code.org/1d7330cc481e1094c25e830d87c3a53b-image-1446443737305.gif" width="450" style="float:right; margin-left:30px">
<br>
Imagine you wanted so simulate flipping a coin, and keep track of how many heads in a row you flip. You won’t know how many times you flip the coin before it comes up tails, but you want to keep flipping until that happens. 
<br><br>
In english: “while the coin is flip turns up to heads, continue flipping and record the number of times it comes up heads.” Check out the short program on the right, which shows how you might write a program that uses a while loop for this coin flipping simulation.


