#### Introduction to Arrays

##### Vocabulary

- **Array**: a data type that holds a list of items. An array can be used like any other variable and gives us the ability to store information for use while the program is running. With an array we can keep track of lots of pieces of information all under one name. 
<br><br>
When declaring an array we need to set some initial values. for example, if we wanted to do something similar to the coin flipping simulation described above, we could start with `var coinFaces = ["heads","tails”];`
<br><br>
The elements stored in an array are each assigned an `index`, or numeric value related the position of the item relative to the list. Indexes start at 0. In the example above, `heads` is stored at index 0 and `tails` is at index 1. 
<br><br>
If we want to **retrieve the value of an element in the array**, we just need to reference the index of the item. For example, if we wanted to print the word “heads” from the array, we would include `write(coinFaces[0]);`
<br><br>
Let’s looks at an example in code. Imagine we’re back to flipping the coin from earlier, but now we just want to know if it comes up heads or tails: 
<br>
<img src="https://images.code.org/b5a8a013306d4ec5aa1ec7286ee6f369-image-1446446698823.gif" width=“550px”>
<br><br>
We can **reassign the value of an element of an array** by referencing a specific index and giving that index a new value. For example, `coinFaces[0]=“face of the coin”;` This line would change the value of `coinFaces[0]`from “heads” to “face of the coin” 
<br><br>
We can also **add elements** to the array by using the gets operator (‘=‘) with an index that is one greater than the current size of the array. For example, if we wanted to add another element to our `coinFaces` array, we might do this:`coinFaces[2] = “neither - the coin landed on its edge!”;` After adding this line of code, coinFaces would have three elements, “heads”, “tales”, “neither - the coin landed on its edge!”

- **For Loop**: a looping structure that is used when you know how often you’ll loop. The `for` loop repeats statements like a `while` loop, but adds an initialization and final expression step, like this:
<br><br>
`for (initialization; condition; final expression) {
    code to execute
}`
<br><br>
A common usage of a for-loop in JavaScript is simply to use it as a "repeat loop" - a block of code that defines how many times you want some lines of code to repeat. This is what we saw early in the unit, but now we can control each of the statements that initialize the counter variable, define the exit condition, and define the unit of incrementation for the counter. 
<br><br>
Here is a breakdown of the meaning the individual statements of a `for` loop:

  - **Statement 1:** “initialization” (for example, `var i = 0;` —>  "Create a variable called i and set it to 0”) -- creates the counter variable and initializes the value. This piece is executed before the loop starts
  - **Statement 2: ** “condition” (for example, `i < 10;` —> “While i is less than 10”) -- condition for continuing to run the loop
  - **Statement 3: ** “incrementing value” (for example, `i++` —>  "Increase (increment) i by 1”) -- increment the counter by some value. This piece is executed each time after the last line of code in the loop is run, before the condition is checked again



